[1] Acute watery diarrhea - Ethiopia (Dire Dawa)
Date: Mon 9 Oct 2017 18:27:54 EAT
Source: Xinhua News Agency [edited]
http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2017-10/09/c_136667475.htm


An acute watery diarrhea (AWD) disease outbreak in Ethiopia's 2nd largest city Dire Dawa, 446 km [277 mi] east of Ethiopia's capital Addis Ababa, has infected 127 people in September 2017, an Ethiopian official said on Mon 9 Oct 2017. Speaking to journalists, Muluken Argaw, Dire Dawa city Health Bureau chief, said the infected people are being treated in the city's main hospital and several have already been discharged after finishing their treatment. Araw cited lack of proper waste disposal means, unsanitary toilet uses and failure to properly cook vegetable foods as reasons behind the diarrhea outbreak.

Several major cities in Ethiopia including Addis Ababa, Mekelle, and Bahir Dar have recorded AWD outbreaks that infected thousands earlier in 2017, exacerbated by unsanitary health practices and Ethiopia's rainy season which stretches from Late June until mid-September.

Ethiopia Federal Ministry of Health (FMoH), regional, and cities health bureaus have also been combating the diarrhea outbreak by treating unhygienic conditions in factories and agricultural areas. FMoH is also currently engaged in educational programs on the cause of AWD
and ways to prevent and treat it.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[AWD is usually used as a euphemism for cholera especially in reports from Sudan and Ethiopia. Dire Dawa is one of 2 chartered cities (astedader akabibi) in Ethiopia (the other being the capital, Addis Ababa). It is divided administratively into 2 woredas (districts), the city proper and the non-urban woreda of Gurgura and can be seen on a map at https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dire_Dawa. - Mod.LL

