[4] Cholera - Congo DR (Haut Lomami, Kasai Oriental provinces)
Date: Wed 4 Oct 2017 13:51 CAT
Source: Radio Okapi [in French, machine trans., edited]]
https://goo.gl/TgEKsf


More than 2000 cases of cholera, including 70 deaths, were recorded in the province of Upper Lomami in early October 2017. These figures were provided at the end of the evaluation meeting chaired last weekend [30 Sep-1 Oct 2017] by the governor of the province. Health authorities have revealed that of the 16 health zones in the province, 7 are affected by the cholera epidemic. These authorities denounce the lack of inputs that do not favor the management of cholera cases in Kamina. Most cholera treatment centers do not have enough dehydration fluids and chlorine. Health officials do not have enough resources to move to sites or centers affected by the epidemic.

In Kasai-Oriental, the health zone of Kabeya Kamuanga is on maximum alert against cholera. Since Thu 28 Sep 2017, the populations of the city of Keena Nkuna and all the 15 areas of this health zone are called to strict observance of the practices of prevention of the epidemic.

An artisanal diamond digger began to have diarrhea and died 8 hours later. The health zone speaks of it as a suspect case, which could also be negative. Since the death occurred at home, no analysis could be made to confirm or disprove the case. Nevertheless, measures were taken to disinfect the body, the residence of the deceased, and all the people who had transported it with bare hands, from the diamond mine to the city.

72 hours later, no other suspect cases have been reported, says Dr Moise Kalonji, chief medical officer of Kabeya Kamuanga health zone. Meanwhile, awareness-raising continues in the city of Keena Nkuna, capital of the territory, in all health areas, and along the rivers.

--
